This change flips us to use tarballs, which are *an order of magnitude smaller* than the .zip files. This can make a big difference, especially on slow connections.\n\nThis change will affect both new users, and existing users if and only if they're using the default repository settings.",

    "title": "Version Edit Transformer",
    "user": {
      "login": "dbent",

      "avatar_url": "https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/1547727?v=3",
      "gravatar_id": "",

      "html_url": "https://github.com/dbent",

      "following_url": "https://api.github.com/users/dbent/following{/other_user}",
      "gists_url": "https://api.github.com/users/dbent/gists{/gist_id}",
      "starred_url": "https://api.github.com/users/dbent/starred{/owner}{/repo}",
      "subscriptions_url": "https://api.github.com/users/dbent/subscriptions",
      "organizations_url": "https://api.github.com/users/dbent/orgs",
      "repos_url": "https://api.github.com/users/dbent/repos",
      "events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/dbent/events{/privacy}",
      "received_events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/dbent/received_events",
      "type": "User",
      "site_admin": false
    },
    "body": "Spun-off of #1320 from @plague006.\r\n\r\nThis adds a new `ITransformer`, `VersionEditTransformer`, that uses regexes (there's no problem that can't be solved with more regexes) to allow simple editing of version strings.\r\n\r\nThe full example is:\r\n\r\n```json\r\n{\r\n    \"spec_version\": 1,\r\n    \"identifier\": \"AwesomeMod\",\r\n    \"x_netkan_version_edit\": {\r\n        \"find\": \"^[vV]?(?<version>.+)$\",\r\n        \"replace\": \"${version}\",\r\n        \"strict\": true\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\n`find` is a standard .NET regular expression. `replace` is a .NET regular expression [substitution string](https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ewy2t5e0%28v=vs.110%29.aspx).\r\n\r\nWhat the example says is \"The version string may start with an uppercase or lowercase `v`, in which case edit the version to be just whatever proceeds the `v`\". `strict` toggles whether or not the transformer should throw an exception if `find` fails to match on the version string.\r\n\r\nThe default value of `replace` is `${version}`. The default value of `strict` is `true`. Therefore the above example can be simplified to:\r\n\r\n```json\r\n{\r\n    \"spec_version\": 1,\r\n    \"identifier\": \"AwesomeMod\",\r\n    \"x_netkan_version_edit\": {\r\n        \"find\": \"^[vV]?(?<version>.+)$\"\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nIf `x_netkan_version_edit` is a string instead of an object, its value is treated as the value of `find`. Therefore the example can be simplified down to:\r\n\r\n```json\r\n{\r\n    \"spec_version\": 1,\r\n    \"identifier\": \"AwesomeMod\",\r\n    \"x_netkan_version_edit\": \"^[vV]?(?<version>.+)$\"\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nBecause we're using full regular expressions and substitution strings, we can come up with all sorts of wacky subs:\r\n\r\n```json\r\n{\r\n    \"spec_version\": 1,\r\n    \"identifier\": \"AwesomeMod\",\r\n    \"version\": \"1.2.3\",\r\n    \"x_netkan_version_edit\": {\r\n        \"find\": \"^(?<major>\\\\d+)\\\\.(?<minor>\\\\d+)\\\\.(?<patch>\\\\d+)$\",\r\n        \"replace\": \"${patch}.${minor}.${major}\"\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nwould produce:\r\n\r\n\r\n```json\r\n{\r\n    \"spec_version\": 1,\r\n    \"identifier\": \"AwesomeMod\",\r\n    \"version\": \"3.2.1\"\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nMy recommendation is that we use this to strip wacky version strings down to their basic value, so we don't have to deal with leading-Vs (or lack thereof), code names in version strings, stability identifiers (alpha, beta), KSP version identifiers, or anything else. Using this would very likely lead to an epoch bump for the mod.",

      "type": "User",
      "site_admin": false
    },
    "body": "The order of properties in the final `.ckan` output of Netkan is currently dependent on the order in which code is executed by the various transformers. This PR adds a new `ITransformer`, `PropertySortTransformer` that is added to the very end of the pipeline.\r\n\r\n`PropertySortTransformer` has an internal list of known properties and will sort the properties in a well defined order (unknown properties are placed just before the `x_generated_by` property in alphabetical order, with `x_` properties always sorting last).\r\n\r\nThis means the output of Netkan should remain relatively stable with all sorts of changes.\r\n\r\nSort order was chosen based on what I feel is an intuitive reading order when looking at `.ckan` files, and mirrors the typical order found in handcrafted `.ckan` files.",
    "created_at": "2015-07-16T18:05:13Z",
    "updated_at": "2015-07-20T13:10:34Z",

      "events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/dbent/events{/privacy}",
      "received_events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/dbent/received_events",
      "type": "User",
      "site_admin": false
    },
    "body": "This PR makes the handling of version information found in internal `.version` files more robust. In practical experience the internal `.version` files aren't remarkably accurate, so we make the two following changes:\r\n\r\n- If the metadata already contains a `version` field, such as from KerbalStuff or a GitHub tag, we **do not override** it with the value found in the `.version` file.\r\n- KSP version information is calculated by \"merging\" the values that are already in the metadata and what we find in the `.version` file. A common example would be if some mod on KerbalStuff indicates that it's compatible with a version of KSP later than what it specifies in its `.version` file. In that case we calculate a minimum version from the `.version` file and a maximum version from the KerbalStuff metadata.\r\n- Add support for \"build\" component in AVC version, only added if present.\r\n\r\nThe `CorrectlyCalculatesKspVersionInfo` test contains a lot of cases. Please add any additional cases you think requires testing.\r\n",

It lists the information as a column in the main mod listing, and as a field in the mod info pane. I removed the homepage column because it wasn't functional, and also an impractical way to view that information. All columns are resized and auto-resize is disabled. I'm running windows and tested at 1080 as well as 720 and it looked the same. I don't have the ability to check how it looks under other OSes.\r\n\r\nAll the column width changes can be reverted simply with a revert of d630fee if needed.\r\n\r\nTest cases specifically for compatibility addition:\r\nksp_version set long (1.0.4): [X]Science\r\nksp_version set short (1.0): Action Groups Extended\r\nksp_version_max (1.0.99): AGroupOnStage\r\nksp_version_min with no max (0.25): 6S Service Compartment Tubes\r\nno version information: Active Texture Management - X86\r\n\r\nPotential issue I wasn't able to test for:\r\n~~If an installed mod has a new version, will it show the compatibility for the current version or the upgrade?~~ @Postremus let me know via IRC that this won't be an issue.",

    "title": "Netkan Refactoring",
    "user": {
      "login": "dbent",
      "id": 1547727,
      "avatar_url": "https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/1547727?v=3",
      "gravatar_id": "",
      "url": "https://api.github.com/users/dbent",
      "html_url": "https://github.com/dbent",

      "following_url": "https://api.github.com/users/dbent/following{/other_user}",
      "gists_url": "https://api.github.com/users/dbent/gists{/gist_id}",
      "starred_url": "https://api.github.com/users/dbent/starred{/owner}{/repo}",
      "subscriptions_url": "https://api.github.com/users/dbent/subscriptions",
      "organizations_url": "https://api.github.com/users/dbent/orgs",
      "repos_url": "https://api.github.com/users/dbent/repos",
      "events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/dbent/events{/privacy}",
      "received_events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/dbent/received_events",
      "type": "User",
      "site_admin": false
    },
    "body": "This is a mondo refactoring of NetKAN. Viewing the diff is a pretty useless way to review this, I'd recommend just stepping through the code in sequence. This refactoring does a few different things:\r\n\r\n- Refactors the entire \"pipeline\" into 5 obvious steps:\r\n  1. Read `.netkan`\r\n  2. Validate `.netkan`\r\n  3. Transform `.netkan` into `.ckan`\r\n  4. Validate `.ckan`\r\n  5. Write `.ckan`\r\n- Includes the changes in #1204\r\n- Includes the changes in #1206\r\n- Adds a bunch more tests\r\n- Changed a bunch of stuff to be more idiomatic C#\r\n\r\n##### Pipeline\r\nThe major refactoring is the introduction of `ITransformer` and `IValidator`. An `ITransformer` has a single method, `Metadata Transform(Metadata)`, that takes a `Metadata` object (a wrapper around a plain `JObject`, that exposes some useful parsed fields) and produces another `Metadata` object. For simplicity's sake `Metadata` objects are immutable. *Every* alternation necessary to turn a `.netkan` into a `.ckan` is implemented as an `ITransformer`. There are 13 \"normal\" implementations of `ITransformer`, called in this specific sequence:\r\n\r\n- `MetaNetkanTransformer` Perform a recursive lookup of another NetKAN file.\r\n- `KerbalstuffTransformer` Looks up data from Kerbal Stuff.\r\n- `GithubTransformer` Looks up data from GitHub.\r\n- `HttpTransformer` Looks up data from an arbitrary HTTP endpoint.\r\n- `JenkinsTransformer` Looks up data from a Jenkins build server.\r\n- `InternalCkanTransformer` Populates data from a CKAN file included in the distribution package.\r\n- `AvcTransformer` Populates version data from an AVC version file included in the distribution package.\r\n- `ForcedVTransformer` Prepends the letter 'v' to the version if necessary.\r\n- `EpochTransformer` Uses a particular version epoch if necessary.\r\n- `VersionedOverrideTransformer` Overrides properties based on the version.\r\n- `DownloadSizeTransformer` Adds the size of the download.\r\n- `GeneratedByTransformer` Adds a property to indicate the program responsible for generating the metadata.\r\n- `StripNetkanMetadataTransformer` Removes metadata useful only to NetKAN.\r\n\r\nIf a particular `ITransformer` isn't applicable to the current state of the `Metadata`, it simply passes the `Metadata` through the pipeline unchanged.\r\n\r\nThere is also one \"special\" `ITransformer`, `NetkanTransformer`, that can transform NetKAN metadata into CKAN metadata, it does this by having knowledge of all the other transformers and calling them in the aforementioned sequence.\r\n\r\nNetKAN was effectively already operating as a pipeline but the implementation wasn't explicit. I think this is easier to reason about and change, and probably most importantly: *test*. Every `ITransformer` does *one* thing (for god's sake I have a `GeneratedByTransformer`!) that makes its behavior obvious and testable. This also drastically reduces redundant code; inspecting CKANs in zip files is now done *once*, adding the size of the download is now done *once*, etc.\r\n\r\nI've also introduced an `IValidator` interface that has a single method `void Validate(Metadata)` that takes a `Metadata` object and either does nothing if it passes validation or throws an exception if it doesn't. There are two special `IValidator` implementations: `NetkanValidator` which is used to validate the incoming metadata from the `.netkan` file and `CkanValidator` which is used to validate the outgoing metadata before it's written to the `.ckan` file.\r\n\r\n##### MetaNetKANs\r\nThis folds the changes in from #1204. Basically a `$kref` of `#/ckan/netkan` is used to point to a `.netkan` file hosted somehow which is then consumed as if all its contents were included in the original `.netkan`. The recursion only goes one level, if the target `.netkan` is itself a MetaNetKAN then an exception is thrown.\r\n\r\n##### Tests\r\nI've added a bunch of tests for this stuff. Here is the [coverage report](https://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/u/123465/CKAN/NetKANTests-20150630.html) for this branch. I've also added [Moq](https://github.com/Moq/moq4) as a tests-only dependency to mock out interfaced dependencies. I've committed the package to source control like the others, but at some point in the future I'd like to modify the build to remove the committed packages and just use NuGet to restore them on-demand.",

      "site_admin": false
    },
    "body": "This is a rough implementation of #865.\r\n\r\nIt supports the following:\r\n\r\n- Allows you to specify `#/ckan/netkan` `$kref` properties, which are then downloaded and processed automatically.\r\n- The `spec_version` used in the final output `.ckan` is the higher of the two specified in the metanetkan or the target netkan.\r\n- Properties specified in the metanetkan override properties specified in the target netkan.\r\n\r\nAn example usage:\r\n```json\r\n{\r\n    \"spec_version\": \"v1.6\",\r\n    \"identifier\": \"HotSpot\",\r\n    \"$kref\": \"#/ckan/netkan/https://raw.githubusercontent.com/KSP-CKAN/NetKAN/master/NetKAN/HotSpot.netkan\",\r\n    \"license\": \"restricted\"\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nProduces the following ckan:\r\n```json\r\n{\r\n    \"spec_version\": \"v1.6\",\r\n    \"identifier\": \"HotSpot\",\r\n    \"depends\": [\r\n        {\r\n            \"name\": \"ModuleManager\",\r\n            \"min_version\": \"2.6.5\"\r\n        }\r\n    ],\r\n    \"resources\": {\r\n        \"homepage\": \"http://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/threads/123967\",\r\n        \"repository\": \"https://github.com/Apokee/HotSpot\",\r\n        \"kerbalstuff\": \"https://kerbalstuff.com/mod/937/Hot%20Spot\"\r\n    },\r\n    \"ksp_version\": \"1.0.4\",\r\n    \"name\": \"Hot Spot\",\r\n    \"license\": \"restricted\",\r\n    \"abstract\": \"Display better thermal data.\",\r\n    \"author\": \"dbb\",\r\n    \"version\": \"0.4.2\",\r\n    \"download\": \"https://kerbalstuff.com/mod/937/Hot%20Spot/download/0.4.2\",\r\n    \"x_generated_by\": \"netkan\",\r\n    \"x_screenshot\": \"https://kerbalstuff.com/content/dbb_49/Hot_Spot/Hot_Spot-1435028274.4356654.png\",\r\n    \"download_size\": 24906\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nNotice that the `spec_version` is `v1.6` and the `license` property is overriden.",

    },
    "body": "While the spec has always had strict requirements as to what characters\nare allowed in versions, this has not been reflected by our software.\nIndeed, we're not really able to restrict how authors version their\nreleases, the best we can do is hope they're sane, or bump the epoch\nif they're not.\n\nThis change alters the spec to weaken the requirement on spec numbers\nto be a recommendation, reflecting how we actually handle things.\n\nThis *is* changing the spec as written, but it's matching reality, so\nwe're not changing what users see. Even so, discussion is welcome (even\nafter this is merged).\n\nCloses #1174.\nNot as cool as #834.\n\n[Our policy on versions](https://github.com/KSP-CKAN/CKAN/blob/master/policy/version-comparison.md) should be kept in mind in discussions.",
